<br>
Gravity assists work on the differential speed going into the gravity well versus coming out.  The way to generate that differential speed is to drop into the well on the same or similar vector that the well generator (the SUN in this case) is traveling.<br>
<br>
So, the questions are which direction is the Sun moving, how fast is it going there,  and is there anything of interest in that direction?<br>
<br>
The Sun heated rocket idea has been thought up before, and is called a Solar Thermal Rocket.  Too low energy for my tastes, but I may be crazy.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
As for using a Solar Thermal Rocket in this scenario....  hmmm.  Actually this is a pretty good idea.  Using hydrogen as reaction mass, you should be able to generate high enough temperatures to obtain Isp over 1500 with a fairly small mirror.  Of course, you have to carry the hydrogen reaction mas TOO the Sun, but you could use the cold hydrogen to cool your spaceship on the way down.<br>
<br>
As a bonus, you could use the mirror to keep your ship from melting!  (Gravity assists work best if you get CLOSE.)<br>
<br>
As for the solar flare?  Did I mention you're crazy?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Also, please forget the whole Orion thingy.  Use a NSWR instead, or if you must stuck to an Orion type of idea, an ICANN-II.  I will say it again, stop living in the 50's guys.  <br>
<br>
It's a whole new millenium, we can do better now.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/17/02 5:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=638250 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ways of getting closer to Interstellar Travel.</span><hr size=1> I don't know how far in the future your looking but we could build solar sails and use lasers to propel them to about 30% of c.  Of course your lasers would need hundreds of terawatts of power which means you'd need some form of nuclear power like fusion or anti-matter to achieve it.  I don't think little windwills would be up to the task but maybe I'm wrong. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 9/17/02 5:53:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utim1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/17/02 9:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ways of getting closer to Interstellar Travel.</span><hr size=1> 1. Fusion rockets can achieve about 10 % to 20%  of Lightspeed at most no matter how good  their design <br>
is.<br>
.<br>
2. A solar sail that uses only natural sunlight and flies within<br>
.01 Au of the sun can achieve about 1% of light speed<br>
at most.<br>
<br>
3. Laser/maser powered solar sails can accelerate a ship <br>
as close to light speed as you want provided that enough laser/maser power is availible.<br>
<br>
4. A  Solar gravitational slingshot  that comes close to the sun  can get a spacecraft up to about 300 kilometers per second at most (This is 1/1000 of light speed).<br>
<br>
5. Matter-antimatter annhilation powered pion rockets<br>
can get a ship up to from 70% to - 90% of light speed.<br>
<br>
6. Laser/maser electric powered  ion drive rockets and ramjets can accelerate a ship to near the speed of light if enough laser maser power is availible.<br>
<br>
7.Nuclear electric powered interstellar ramjets can slowly,<br>
and they can theoreticly accelerate a ship to near the speed of light given enough time, and enough electric power .<br>
  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uastrogeologist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>astrogeologist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/17/02 9:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Time for the Stars.</span><hr size=1> Ideas that might work in conjunction with a nuclear rocket. Ok. So you get as close as possible to gain a Sun gravity assist, without melting. You can harness the enormous heat energy available but it costs you reaction mass.<br>
<br>
The crazy idea of surfing a solar flare. It's an intriguing notion. How big is this plasma wave and how dense? What kind of temperatures are we talking about. Far lower than the internal temperatures of the Sun I'm sure. I recall reading in a Dr Who comic that the surface of the Sun is cooler than the palm of your hand. Not the best reference I know. If it could be done then its not disimilar to a laser light sail. No reaction mass necessary. External power. Ten times slower than light but far denser. First you have to catch one though. Can a solar flare be induced? What causes them? Is it known? Could they be directed to the ship. Like lightning is drawn by metal.<br>
This is very interesting. You could also unfurl an immense lightsail close to the Sun to get as much light push as possible. Interstellar flight within a reasonable timeframe might require many propulsion technologies to be combined.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utim1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/18/02 9:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=134.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Time for the Stars.</span><hr size=1> Solar flares of varying intensity occurr 24 /7 on the sun<br>
and thus create a 500 kilometer per second solar wind.<br>
A man named wingley has designed an electric powered<br>
 magnetic plasma sail   that can harnass the solar wind to<br>
